      <h2>6. Data Storage and Encryption</h2>
      <p>DocArmor encrypts all stored documents using AES-256 via Apple's CryptoKit framework. Your encryption key is stored in the iOS Keychain on your device and never leaves your device.</p>
      <p><strong>DocArmor explicitly disables iCloud sync.</strong> Your documents are not backed up to iCloud, iCloud Drive, or any cloud service. Documents exist only in the App's local storage container on your device.</p>
      <p>Standard iOS device backups (iCloud Backup or local Finder/iTunes backups) may include the App's encrypted container as part of a full device backup, subject to Apple's backup policies.</p>

      <h2>7. Data Loss Warning</h2>
      <p><strong>Uninstalling DocArmor permanently and irrecoverably deletes all documents stored in the App.</strong> Because there is no cloud backup, no server-side copy, and no Katafract account, there is no way for us or for you to recover deleted documents after the App is removed.</p>
      <p>You are solely responsible for exporting or otherwise preserving any documents you need before uninstalling the App. Katafract is not liable for any data loss resulting from uninstalling the App, device failure, device reset, or any other cause.</p>

      <h2>8. Face ID and Touch ID</h2>
      <p>DocArmor uses Apple's Local Authentication framework to require biometric verification before granting access to your documents. The App receives only a pass/fail result from the framework; it never accesses, reads, or stores your biometric data. Biometric data remains in your device's Secure Enclave at all times.</p>
      <p>If biometric authentication is unavailable or fails repeatedly, iOS may offer a device passcode fallback. Katafract has no control over or visibility into this fallback process.</p>

      <h2>9. Document Scanner</h2>
      <p>The built-in document scanner uses Apple's VisionKit framework and processes the camera feed entirely on-device. Scanned images are passed directly to the App's encryption pipeline and are not written to your photo library or cached to disk in unencrypted form.</p>

      <h2>10. Photo Library Access</h2>
      <p>When you choose to import a photo from your library into DocArmor, the App requests photo library read access for that specific operation. The imported image is immediately encrypted and stored in the local vault. DocArmor does not index, retain persistent access to, or upload your photo library.</p>

